05764nam a22008295i 9780228009573DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280095737 a10.1515/97802280095732doi  a(DE-B1597)656005  a(OCoLC)1261632786  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9189.5b.H65 2021 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04aC810.9/891622231 aHolmgren, Michele, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanada to Ireland :bPoetry, Politics, and the Shaping of Canadian Nationalism, 1788–1900 /cMichele Holmgren. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (472 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCarleton Library Series ;v25800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tIrish Patriots in Canada -- tIsaac Weld (1774–1856) -- tStephen Dickson (1761–1799) -- tUnited Irishmen in Canada -- tLord Edward Fitzgerald (1763–1798) -- tThomas Moore (1779–1852) -- tIrish Emigrant Writers and Emancipation -- tAdam Kidd (1803–1831) -- tStandish O’Grady Bennett (fl. 1776–1846) -- tRebellion, Responsible Government, and Satire -- tCharles Dawson Shanly (1811–1875) -- tJames McCarroll (1814–1892) -- tYoung Ireland and Young Canada -- tThomas D’Arcy McGee (1825–1868) -- tJohn Reade (1837–1919) -- tIreland to the Canadian West -- tNicholas Flood Davin (1840–1901) -- tIsabella Valancy Crawford (c. 1847–1887) -- tAn Irish Speaker in Canada -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, Irish writers played a key role in transatlantic cultural conversations – among Canada, Britain, France, America, and Indigenous nations – that shaped Canadian nationalism. Nationalism in Ireland was likewise influenced by the literary works of Irish migrants and visitors to Canada.Canada to Ireland explores the poetry and prose of twelve Irish writers and nationalists in Canada between 1788 and 1900, including Thomas Moore, Adam Kidd, Lord Edward Fitzgerald, Thomas D’Arcy McGee, James McCarroll, Nicholas Flood Davin, and Isabella Valancy Crawford. Many of these writers were involved in Irish political causes, including those of the Patriots, the United Irish, Emancipation, Repeal, and Young Ireland, and their work explores the similar ways in which nationalists in Ireland and Indigenous and settler communities in Canada retained their cultural identities and sought autonomy from Britain. Initially writing for an audience in Ireland, they highlighted features of the landscape and culture that they regarded as distinctively Canadian and that were later invoked as powerful unifying symbols by Canadian nationalists. Michele Holmgren shows how these Irish writers and movements are essential to understanding the tenor of early Canadian literary nationalism and political debates concerning Confederation, imperial unity, and western expansion.Canada to Ireland convincingly demonstrates that Canadian cultural nationalism left its mark on both countries. Contemporary decolonization movements in Canada and current cultural exchanges between Ireland and Indigenous peoples make this a timely and relevant study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexIrish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexIrish influences. 0aCanadian literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian, in literature. 0aNationalism in literature. 0aPolitics in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAdam Kidd.  aCharles Dawson Shanly.  aFenian Brotherhood.